<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06273115 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06273115 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; REGULATION; CHANGE; EAST; EUROPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  NEWLY independent Baltic states are now requiring visas for Americans, thoughthe recent upheaval in the Soviet Union has not changed visa requirements forthe other newly independent republics.;   The states -- Estonia, Latvia andLithuania -- have begun issuing visas at the point of entry and, in the caseof Lithuania, at some consular offices. But representatives of all threenations indicated a desire to eventually require just a valid passport forsomeone from a friendly nation.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  INDEPENDENCE CALLS FOR A NEW SET OF VISAS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Travelers' Advisory  </MEMO><TEXT>     All three issue visas at the border free of charge. Lithuania will alsoissue visas at its consular offices for a $25 fee. The visas are good for 90days but will be granted for longer periods upon request.;   &quot;For other unionrepublics, nothing has changed,&quot; said a spokesman at the Soviet Embassy inWashington. American citizens wishing to visit the country must obtain visasthrough the Embassy. A tourist visa, good for up to three months, costs $25.;  For visa information: Estonian Consulate in New York, (212) 247-1450; LatvianLegation in Washington, (202) 726-8213; Lithuanian Consulate in New York,(212) 877-4552; Soviet Embassy in Washington, (202) 939-8907; Soviet Consulatein New York, (212) 348-0926.;   Also, be advised the U.S. State Department isstill warning about medical conditions in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.;   Inall three countries, the State Department notes, &quot;medical care . . . does notmeet Western standards. There is a severe shortage of basic medical supplies,including disposable needles, anesthetics and antibiotics. Tourists in frailhealth are strongly advised not to visit.&quot;;   Also, consular assistance cannotbe provided until embassies have been established.; Mexico; (box) The roadtrip from Mexico City to Puebla takes about 45 minutes less thanks to the newIgnacio Zaragoza Causeway, which opened in August. The eight-lane roadconnects with Highway 150, a toll road to Puebla and Veracruz. The 81-milejourney now takes about 90 minutes.;   Before the tree-lined causeway opened,the exit road east through an industrial neighborhood of Mexico City was aterrible bottleneck. Traffic slowed to a halt during rush hour to accommodatebuses and pedestrians. The new road features 6 vehicular overpasses and 21pedestrian bridges and is free of traffic lights.; Ecologically speaking;Documentary film maker Jorge Monzon and producer Mark Adams will speak Mondayat Bookshop Santa Cruz about their Costa Rica Rainforest Video Project.;  Their plan is to get some people who care about the rain forest, putcamcorders in their hand and take them to Costa Rica to make a documentary forpublic access cable television. The trip is planned for Nov. 9-23.;   Whatshould perhaps be called Booktent Santa Cruz is located in Pavilion G on CedarStreet. Phone (408) 423-0900 for the book store, (408) 761-5551 for Adams.;Wild blue yonder; (box) For anyone who has ever wanted to ride in an airship,Virgin Atlantic has started blimp tours in Orlando, Fla. Five- to seven-minuteflights are $28.50 per person, 15-minute flights $75, 45 minutes $150, andhour-long, champagne cruises $185. Blimps can hold three adults, one child andthe captain. Flights are daily. Call a few days ahead for weekend flights orthe same day for weekdays. (407) 841-UPUP.; The Netherlands; The Heinekenbrewery in Amsterdam has reopened as a museum. The building atStadhouderskade, constructed in 1932, was closed three years ago when Heinekenbuilt a bigger, more modern plant outside of Leiden, with better accessibilityfor large trucks.;   The museum, which opened in May, provides information onthe history of the Heineken company and its brewing process. Through May 14there are three tours each morning. The museum, near the Liedesplein incentral Amsterdam, is closed on weekends.;   A special entrance is availablefor people in wheelchairs. The entrance fee of 25 cents a person is donated tocharities. Visitors aged 16 or over are given a free glass of beer. Moreinformation: Heineken Brouwerij Amsterdam, 78 Stadhouderskade, 1072 N.V.Amsterdam, Netherlands; telephone 539239.; Spain; From Nov. 1 to April 1,travelers to Spain can save on lodging at some of the 40 government-operatedparadors.;   Based on a minimum of two nights' stay, rates range from $140 to$156 per night, double occupancy, and include breakfast and a choice of lunchor dinner. The same rates apply to single occupancy.;   Contact MarketingAhead Hotel Representatives, 433 5th Ave., New York, N.Y. 10016; (212)686-9213.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910929  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3T  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  741  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday, September 29, 199100273115,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>